Zhang Qiang (Chinese: 张蔷; born 1967), also known as Sara Chang, is a Chinese singer who started her career in the mid 1980s.
In these years, Taiwanese and Hong Kong singers such as Teresa Teng were prominent, and fascinated the young people.
From then on, she would release 20 studio albums in the next two years.
Tokyo Nights, Zhang's first cover album, was released in early 1985.
Zhang was initially expected to earn 800 yuan a month.
She followed the trends of the '80s both musically and visually, which helped to make her popular.
Her face could be seen nowhere in the media, only the covers of her albums featured photos of her, and the only information her fans could find, were nothing else than her releases.
From 1988 to 1992, when she gave birth to her first child, when she was 19, she started releasing only one album per year.
In this year, Zhang started feeling that she could not cover more songs because she already had covered too many.
Apart from that, in 1987, she went to Australia to study and from 1988 to 1992, she only recorded one album per year.
In the middle 1990s, the Mainland Chinese entertainment industry was starting to take off.

Singers such as Na Ying, Sun Nan, Sun Yue and Yang Yuying were starting to make a name in the entertainment world and some famous singers such as Faye Wong, had returned to the mainland, working with local producers such as Zhang Yadong.
